# ============================================================
# .cursorrules — Production AI Coding Rules
# Applies to: Cursor Chat, Composer, Agent
# Stack: NestJS + Prisma + PostgreSQL | React Web App
# Principle: Correctness + simplicity over speed
# ============================================================


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 0 — REPOSITORY STRUCTURE
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

# This repo contains 2 applications:
#
#   /backend   — NestJS + Prisma + PostgreSQL (APIs, auth, business logic)
#   /frontend  — React web app



## 1.4 Goal-Driven Execution
- Define clear success criteria before writing any code.
- Work iteratively toward verification.
- Stop when the defined goal is achieved — do not over-engineer.

## 1.5 Checkpoint in Multi-Step Tasks (Agent Mode)
After each major step, always summarise:
  - What was changed
  - What is verified
  - What is pending
Stop if context becomes unclear or incomplete.

## 1.6 Fail Loud
- Never silently skip steps.
- Never mark incomplete work as done.
- Always surface uncertainty or missing validation.
- Edge cases must be explicitly verified or flagged.

## 1.7 Read Before Writing
- Inspect related files before making changes.
- Understand exports, usage, and dependencies first.
- If structure or intent is unclear, ask before extending.

## 1.8 Resolve Conflicts Explicitly
- Do not merge conflicting patterns.
- Choose the most recent or most consistently used pattern.
- Explain the choice.
- Flag other inconsistencies for later cleanup.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 2 — UNIVERSAL CODE QUALITY (ALL APPS)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Code must be clean, readable, and production-ready at all times.
- No dead code, unused imports, or unreachable logic.
- No duplicate logic — reuse where appropriate.
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility).
- Prefer clarity over cleverness.
- Prefer early returns over deeply nested conditionals.
- Follow existing naming conventions strictly per folder.
- Ensure proper error handling — no silent failures.
- Remove all console.log statements before marking work complete.
- No file should exceed 250 lines of code.
  → If a file grows beyond this: split into logical modules, services, or components.
  → Extract reusable utilities where appropriate.
  → This rule is non-negotiable — never extend a large file instead of refactoring.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 3 — TYPESCRIPT (ALL APPS)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Use TypeScript everywhere, in both apps.
- Enable strict mode in tsconfig.
- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` when type is truly unknown, then narrow it.
- Define explicit types for: props, API responses, hooks, utilities, function params.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; prefer `type` for unions and intersections.
- Use enums only when values are truly fixed and meaningful.
- Use generics when applicable.
- Avoid type assertions (`as`) unless absolutely necessary.
- Export shared types from dedicated `.types.ts` files.

✅
```ts
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}
```

❌
```ts
const user: any = {};
const data = response as SomeType;
```


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 4 — NAMING CONVENTIONS (ALL APPS)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Files
- Components:              PascalCase       → UserCard.tsx, ProfileModal.tsx
- Hooks:                   camelCase        → useUsers.ts, useAuth.ts
- Utilities:               camelCase        → formatDate.ts, truncateText.ts
- Types:                   kebab-case       → user.types.ts, auth.types.ts
- API files:               kebab-case       → user.api.ts, post.api.ts
- Query hooks:             kebab-case       → user.query.ts, auth.query.ts
- Constants:               kebab-case       → query-keys.ts, routes.ts
- NestJS modules:          kebab-case       → user.controller.ts, user.service.ts

## Variables & Functions
- Variables:               camelCase        → userId, isLoading
- Functions:               camelCase        → getUser(), formatPrice()
- Constants:               UPPER_SNAKE_CASE → MAX_RETRY, API_URL
- Classes:                 PascalCase       → UserService, AuthGuard
- Interfaces:              PascalCase       → CreateUserDto, UserResponse
- Enums:                   PascalCase       → UserRole, OrderStatus
- Enum values:             UPPER_SNAKE_CASE → UserRole.SUPER_ADMIN

## Folders
- Always use:              kebab-case       → user-profile/, order-items/


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 5 — BACKEND (NestJS + Prisma + PostgreSQL)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 5.1 Module Structure
Every module must follow this exact folder and file layout — no exceptions:

```
<module-name>/
├── dto/
│   ├── create-<module>.dto.ts
│   ├── update-<module>.dto.ts
│   └── query-<module>.dto.ts
├── guards/
│   └── <specific>.guard.ts
├── helpers/
│   └── <module>.helper.ts
├── repository/                    ← optional; auth uses db.service only
│   └── <module>.repository.ts
├── swagger/
│   └── <module>.swagger.ts
├── types/
│   └── <module>.types.ts
├── <module>.controller.ts
├── <module>.service.ts
├── <module>.db.service.ts
└── <module>.module.ts
```

Never invent custom structures per module. Every module must look identical unless documented (e.g. `auth/` has no `repository/` — Prisma lives in `auth.db.service.ts`).

## 5.1b Module Dependencies (NestJS)

- Do NOT import a full feature module when you only need 1–2 services — register those services (+ direct deps) in `providers`.
- Do NOT use `forwardRef(() => AuthModule)` / `forwardRef(() => EmailModule)` between feature modules.
- `EmailModule`: `AuthDbService` in `providers` (not `AuthModule` import).
- `AuthModule`: email services in `providers` (not `EmailModule` import); `AuthDbModule` for auth db layer only.

## 5.2 Layer Responsibilities

### Controller
- Request handling, route decorators, guards, Swagger decorators only.
- ❌ Never put business logic inside controllers.
- ❌ Never put error logic inside controllers.

### Service
- Business logic, validation, events, notifications, orchestration.
- ❌ Never write Prisma queries inside services.

### Db Service
- Prisma queries when no separate repository (auth pattern)
- Cache handling, error mapping, query building, repository coordination when repository exists
- If db.service only delegates to repository with no extra logic, merge into db.service and remove repository

### Repository
- Prisma queries only (optional layer — skip when db.service owns Prisma, see auth/)

```ts
// Only these patterns:
findById(id: string)
findByEmail(email: string)
create(data: CreateUserDto)
update(id: string, data: UpdateUserDto)
delete(id: string)
paginate(query: QueryDto)
```

### DTO
- Request validation using class-validator and class-transformer.
- ❌ Never use plain interfaces for request validation.

### Helpers
- Utility functions, password hashing, transformations, formatting.
- ❌ No database queries inside helpers.

### Types
- Enums, interfaces, response types, Prisma extensions, shared types.

### Guards
- Authentication and authorization only.
- ❌ No business logic inside guards.

### Swagger
- ApiOperation, ApiResponse, ApiBearerAuth decorators.
- Keep all Swagger decorators separate from controllers, inside `/swagger`.

## 5.3 Prisma Rules
- Prisma queries belong in **repository** or **db.service** — never in business services or controllers.

❌
```ts
// user.service.ts
await this.prisma.user.findMany();
```

✅ (with repository)
```ts
// user.repository.ts
async findAll() {
  return this.prisma.user.findMany();
}
```

✅ (without repository — auth)
```ts
// auth.db.service.ts
findUserById(id: string) {
  return this.prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id } });
}
```

## 5.4 N+1 Query Prevention
- Never execute queries inside loops.

❌
```ts
for (const user of users) {
  await prisma.profile.findUnique({ where: { userId: user.id } });
}
```

✅ Use `include`, `select`, joins, `groupBy`, batch queries, or `Promise.all`.
```ts
await prisma.user.findMany({
  include: { profile: true },
});
```

## 5.5 Query Optimisation
- Always use `select` — fetch only required fields.
- Paginate all large list endpoints.
- Use database indexes for all queried columns.
- Avoid unnecessary relation loads.
- Use transactions for multi-step writes.

## 5.6 Error Handling
- Always use the shared `ApiError` utility:
  ```
  src/utils/ApiError.ts
  ```
- Never throw generic `Error` or raw objects.
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes.
- Error messages must be clear and user-friendly.
- Never expose internal implementation details in error responses.
- Services throw errors — controllers never contain error logic.

```ts
// ✅ Correct
throw new ApiError(404, 'User not found');
throw new ApiError(409, 'Email already exists');
throw new ApiError(401, 'Unauthorized');
throw new ApiError(403, 'Permission denied');
throw new ApiError(500, 'Something went wrong');

// ❌ Forbidden
throw new Error('User not found');
throw { status: 400, message: 'Bad Request' };
return { success: false, error: 'Something went wrong' };
```

## 5.7 Response Format
- Always use the shared `ApiResponse` utility:
  ```
  src/utils/ApiResponse.ts
  ```
- Never create custom response objects.
- Never return raw objects from controllers.

```ts
// ✅ Correct
return ApiResponse.success(data, 'User fetched successfully');
return ApiResponse.created(data, 'User created successfully');
return ApiResponse.paginated(data, meta, 'Users fetched successfully');

// ❌ Forbidden
return { success: true, data };
return res.json({ message: 'Success', data });
```

## 5.8 Validation
- Use `class-validator` and `class-transformer` on all DTOs.
- Enable `ValidationPipe` globally with `whitelist: true, forbidNonWhitelisted: true`.
- Sanitise all input — never trust raw user input.
- Validate and whitelist all query params.

```ts
// ✅ DTO example
export class CreateUserDto {
  @IsEmail()
  email: string;

  @IsString()
  @MinLength(8)
  password: string;

  @IsEnum(UserRole)
  role: UserRole;
}
```

## 5.9 Authentication & JWT
- Always validate JWT tokens in guards, not in services or controllers.
- Never expose raw JWT secrets in code — use `ConfigService`.
- Attach the authenticated user to `request.user` via `JwtStrategy`.
- Use `@CurrentUser()` custom decorator to access user in controllers.
- Access and refresh token pattern: short-lived access (15m), longer refresh (7d).
- Hash all passwords with bcrypt (minimum 10 rounds) before storing.
- Never log or return passwords in any response.

## 5.10 Roles & Permissions
- Always use role-based guards (`RolesGuard`) with the `@Roles()` decorator.
- Never hard-code role checks inside services.
- Define all roles in a shared enum.
- Permission checks happen at the guard layer — not in services.

```ts
@Roles(UserRole.ADMIN, UserRole.SUPER_ADMIN)
@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard)
@Get('admin/users')
getUsers() { ... }
```

## 5.11 Logging
- Use NestJS `Logger` (not `console.log`) for all backend logging.
- Log at appropriate levels: `log`, `warn`, `error`, `debug`, `verbose`.
- Always log errors with context (module name).
- Never log passwords, tokens, or sensitive PII.
- In production, structured JSON logging is required.

```ts
private readonly logger = new Logger(UserService.name);
this.logger.log('User created successfully');
this.logger.error('Failed to create user', error.stack);
```

## 5.12 Rate Limiting
- Apply `@Throttle()` to all public-facing endpoints.
- Apply stricter limits to auth endpoints (login, register, forgot-password).
- Use `ThrottlerGuard` globally and override per-endpoint where needed.

```ts
@Throttle({ default: { limit: 5, ttl: 60000 } })
@Post('auth/login')
login() { ... }
```

## 5.13 Security
- Helmet enabled globally.
- CORS configured to whitelist only allowed origins — never use wildcard `*` in production.
- All sensitive config loaded via `ConfigService` (never hardcoded).
- Never commit `.env` files.
- Sanitise file uploads: validate MIME type, extension, and file size.
- Use `express-rate-limit` for additional DDoS protection.
- Parameterised queries only — never string-interpolated SQL.

## 5.14 Swagger / API Documentation
- Every controller endpoint must have:
  - `@ApiOperation({ summary: '...' })`
  - `@ApiResponse({ status: ..., description: '...' })`
  - `@ApiBearerAuth()` where authentication is required
- Keep all Swagger decorators in the `/swagger` folder, not inside the controller.
- Tag all controller methods by module using `@ApiTags`.

## 5.15 Database Migrations
- Never modify the database manually — all changes go through Prisma migrations.
- Never edit existing migration files.
- Migration naming convention: `YYYYMMDD_description_of_change`.
- Always review `prisma migrate diff` before applying in production.
- Seed data lives in `prisma/seed.ts` — never in migrations.

## 5.16 WebSockets
- Use NestJS `@WebSocketGateway()` for real-time features.
- Authenticate WebSocket connections using JWT in the `handleConnection` hook.
- Emit typed events — define event name constants in a shared types file.
- Never handle business logic inside gateways — delegate to services.

## 5.17 Interceptors & Middleware
- Use interceptors for: response transformation, logging, caching headers.
- Use middleware for: request logging, correlation IDs, basic pre-processing.
- Never put business logic inside interceptors or middleware.
- Apply interceptors at the module or controller level — avoid global overuse.

## 5.18 Pipes
- Use `ParseIntPipe`, `ParseUUIDPipe`, and `ValidationPipe` where appropriate.
- Create custom pipes for complex transformations.
- Pipes should be pure and side-effect free.

## 5.19 File Uploads
- Validate: MIME type, file extension, maximum file size.
- Never store file paths or public URLs with sensitive data embedded.
- Use a dedicated service (e.g. S3 wrapper) — never write upload logic in controllers.
- Enforce size limits at the Multer config level.

## 5.20 Backend — Forbidden
❌ Business logic inside controllers
❌ Prisma queries inside services
❌ Prisma queries inside controllers
❌ Raw SQL unless absolutely necessary (and reviewed)
❌ N+1 queries
❌ Database queries inside loops
❌ Returning Prisma entities directly from controllers
❌ Password or token fields in any API response
❌ Files over 250 lines
❌ circular dependencies
❌ Hardcoded secrets or environment values
❌ `console.log` in any backend file
❌ Generic `new Error(...)` throws
❌ Custom ad-hoc response shapes

## 5.21 Backend Folder Structure
```
src/
├── common/
│   ├── decorators/
│   ├── filters/
│   ├── guards/
│   ├── interceptors/
│   ├── middleware/
│   └── pipes/
├── config/
├── modules/
│   ├── auth/
│   ├── user/
│   ├── product/
│   └── ...
├── prisma/
│   └── prisma.service.ts
├── utils/
│   ├── ApiError.ts
│   └── ApiResponse.ts
└── main.ts
```


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 6 — ADMIN DASHBOARD (React + TypeScript)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## 6.1 General Principles
- Write clean, maintainable, and optimised code.
- Prefer composition over duplication.
- Keep components small and reusable (max 250 lines per file).
- Extract complex logic into hooks, utilities, or child components.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders.
- Follow SOLID principles.

## 6.2 Tech Stack (Admin)
### Core
- TypeScript (strict)
- React + React Router

### API
- Axios (configured instance at `src/lib/axios.ts`)
- TanStack Query (useQuery, useMutation, invalidateQueries)

### Styling
- TailwindCSS
- shadcn/ui

### Forms
- React Hook Form + Zod validation

### State
- TanStack Query for server state
- Zustand for complex client state
- React Context for small global state

### Notifications
- Sonner Toast (`toast.success()`, `toast.error()`)

### Utilities
- Lodash, Dayjs, clsx, class-variance-authority

### Quality
- ESLint, Prettier, Husky, lint-staged

## 6.3 API Layer
- Always use the configured Axios instance — never raw `fetch()`.
- API files live at `src/api/` and contain only Axios calls.
- No business logic, no toast notifications, no data transformations inside API files.
- Always define request and response types.

```ts
// src/api/user.api.ts
export const getUsers = (): Promise<ApiResponse<User[]>> =>
  api.get('/admin/users');

export const createUser = (data: CreateUserPayload): Promise<ApiResponse<User>> =>
  api.post('/admin/users', data);
```

## 6.4 Server State (TanStack Query)
- Never call APIs directly inside components.
- Always wrap API calls in custom query/mutation hooks.
- Use `select` to transform response shape at the hook level.
- Use `staleTime` to prevent unnecessary refetches.
- Centralise query keys in `src/constants/query-keys.ts`.

```ts
// src/hooks/api/user.query.ts
export const useUsers = () =>
  useQuery({
    queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.USERS,
    queryFn: getUsers,
    select: (res) => res.data.data,
    staleTime: 1000 * 60 * 5,
  });

export const useCreateUser = () => {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: createUser,
    onSuccess: () => {
      queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.USERS });
      toast.success('User created successfully');
    },
    onError: (err) => toast.error(err.message),
  });
};
```

## 6.5 Forms (Admin)
- Always use React Hook Form + Zod.
- Keep Zod schemas outside components in `src/validations/`.
- Use `zodResolver` to connect schema to form.
- Show field-level validation errors.
- Disable submit while pending (`isPending`).
- Always show success and error toast messages.

```ts
// src/validations/user.validation.ts
export const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email('Invalid email'),
  password: z.string().min(8, 'Minimum 8 characters'),
  role: z.nativeEnum(UserRole),
});
```

## 6.6 Providers
- Use providers for globally shared data: `UserProvider`, `AuthProvider`, `ThemeProvider`.
- Always expose data via custom hooks — never access context directly.
- Location: `src/providers/`.

```ts
// ✅
const { user } = useUser();
// ❌
const { user } = useContext(UserContext);
```

## 6.7 Component Structure
```
pages/UsersPage.tsx          ← UI only, renders components
hooks/api/useUsers.ts        ← data fetching logic
api/user.api.ts              ← Axios calls only
validations/user.validation.ts ← Zod schemas
components/UserTable.tsx     ← reusable table component
```

## 6.8 Loading & Error States
- Every data-fetching screen must handle: `isLoading`, `isError`, empty state.
- Use skeleton loaders — never blank screens.
- Use `toast.error()` for all API errors — never `alert()`.

## 6.9 Performance
- Use `React.memo`, `useMemo`, `useCallback` only when there's a measurable benefit.
- Paginate all large data lists.
- Use `lazy()` + `Suspense` for route-level code splitting.

## 6.10 Admin Folder Structure
```
src/
├── api/
├── assets/
├── components/
├── constants/
├── hooks/
│   ├── api/
│   ├── forms/
│   └── common/
├── layouts/
├── lib/
│   └── axios.ts
├── pages/
├── providers/
├── routes/
├── store/
├── styles/
├── types/
├── utils/
└── validations/
```

## 6.11 Admin — Forbidden
❌ `any` type
❌ `fetch()` — use Axios instance
❌ `alert()` — use toast
❌ API calls directly inside components
❌ Zod schemas inside JSX files
❌ Business logic inside page components
❌ Components larger than 250 lines
❌ Hardcoded query keys
❌ Direct context access (always use custom hooks)
❌ Inline styles
❌ Nested ternary operators
❌ Duplicate utility functions
❌ `console.log` before completion


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 7 — SECURITY STANDARDS (ALL APPS)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Never commit secrets, API keys, tokens, or credentials to source control.
- Always load secrets via environment variables and validate on startup.
- Never log passwords, tokens, or personal identifiable information.
- Validate and sanitise all user input — frontend and backend.
- Apply HTTPS everywhere — reject HTTP in production.
- Use parameterised queries exclusively — no string-interpolated SQL.
- Apply CSRF protection on all state-mutating web endpoints.
- Enforce Content-Security-Policy headers on all web interfaces.
- Rate-limit all authentication and sensitive endpoints.
- Audit all file uploads for type, size, and content.
- Revoke and rotate credentials immediately if exposed.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 8 — TESTING
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Backend
- Unit test all services using Jest.
- Integration test all critical API endpoints using Supertest.
- Mock all external dependencies (Prisma, third-party APIs).
- Test unhappy paths, validation errors, and auth failures — not just happy paths.
- Aim for meaningful coverage on service and repository layers.

## Admin
- Unit test hooks and utilities with Vitest or Jest.
- Component test critical UI interactions with React Testing Library.


## General
- Test file naming: `<name>.spec.ts` for unit, `<name>.e2e.ts` for integration.
- Never test implementation details — test behaviour and outcomes.
- CI must run all tests on every pull request.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 9 — GIT & WORKFLOW
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Commit Messages (Conventional Commits)
```
feat(user): add profile update endpoint
fix(auth): resolve token refresh race condition
refactor(order): split service into sub-services
chore: update dependencies
docs: add API documentation for payment module
test(user): add unit tests for user service
```

## Branch Naming
```
feature/<ticket-id>-short-description
fix/<ticket-id>-short-description
chore/dependency-updates
hotfix/<ticket-id>-short-description
```

## Pull Requests
- Every PR must have a clear description of what changed and why.
- No PR merges without passing CI (lint, type-check, tests).
- Self-review diff before requesting review.
- One logical change per PR — no mixed concerns.

## Husky (Pre-commit)
- ESLint must pass on staged files.
- Prettier must format staged files.
- TypeScript must type-check without errors.
- No `console.log`, `TODO`, or `FIXME` in committed code.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 10 — ENVIRONMENT & CONFIG
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

- All environment variables defined in `.env.example` with comments.
- `.env` files never committed to source control (in `.gitignore`).
- Backend: use NestJS `ConfigModule` with `validationSchema` (Joi or Zod).
- Frontend: use `VITE_` prefix.
- Validate required env vars at application startup — fail fast if missing.
- Separate config per environment: `.env.development`, `.env.staging`, `.env.production`.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 11 — PERFORMANCE & SCALABILITY
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

## Backend
- Paginate all list endpoints — never return unbounded arrays.
- Cache frequent read-heavy queries (Redis or in-memory).
- Use database indexes on all foreign keys and frequently queried columns.
- Use `select` in Prisma to avoid over-fetching.
- Background jobs for heavy/async work (queues — BullMQ).
- Avoid blocking the event loop — no synchronous CPU-heavy operations.

## Frontend
- Paginate or virtualise large data lists.
- Implement query `staleTime` to prevent over-fetching.
- Route-level code splitting with `lazy()` + `Suspense`.
- Optimise images — use correct dimensions and formats.


# ════════════════════════════════════════════════
# QUICK REFERENCE — WHAT TO USE WHERE
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════

| Concern                  | Backend              | Frontend                 |
|--------------------------|----------------------|--------------------------|
| HTTP client              | —                    | Axios instance           |
| Server state             | —                    | TanStack Query           |
| Forms                    | class-validator DTOs | React Hook Form + Zod    |
| Client state             | —                    | Zustand / Context        |
| Notifications            | —                    | Sonner toast             |
| Styling                  | —                    | TailwindCSS + shadcn/ui  |
| Auth tokens              | JWT (ConfigService)  | Axios interceptor        |
| Error handling           | ApiError utility     | toast.error()            |
| Response shape           | ApiResponse utility  | Typed from API response  |
| Logging                  | NestJS Logger        | (none in prod)           |
| DB access                | Repository only      | —                        |
| Validation               | ValidationPipe + DTO | Zod schema               |
